\section{Stop Order Types}{

\strong{Limit Stop Orders} require \code{price}, \code{size}, and \code{stopPrice}. When the market
reaches the \code{stopPrice}, a limit order is placed at the specified \code{price}.
Optional parameters include \code{timeInForce}, \code{cancelAfter}, \code{postOnly}, \code{hidden},
\code{iceberg}, and \code{visibleSize}.

\strong{Market Stop Orders} require \code{stopPrice} and either \code{size} (base currency quantity)
or \code{funds} (quote currency amount), but not both. \code{price} must NOT be specified.
When the market reaches the \code{stopPrice}, a market order executes immediately at
the best available price.

\strong{How stopPrice Triggers Work}:
\itemize{
\item For a \strong{buy} stop order, the stop triggers when the last traded price rises
to or above \code{stopPrice}.
\item For a \strong{sell} stop order, the stop triggers when the last traded price falls
to or below \code{stopPrice}.
\item Once triggered, the stop order is converted to a regular order (limit or market)
and submitted to the matching engine. Trigger checks are based on the last
trade price for the symbol.
}
}

\section{Self-Trade Prevention (STP)}{

Use the \code{stp} parameter to control behaviour when your orders would match each other:
\itemize{
\item \code{"CN"} (Cancel Newest): Cancel the incoming order.
\item \code{"CO"} (Cancel Oldest): Cancel the resting order.
\item \code{"CB"} (Cancel Both): Cancel both orders.
\item \code{"DC"} (Decrement and Cancel): Reduce quantities.
}
}

\section{Time-In-Force Options}{

\itemize{
\item \code{"GTC"} (Good Till Cancelled): Remains until filled or cancelled. Default.
\item \code{"GTT"} (Good Till Time): Cancels after \code{cancelAfter} seconds.
\item \code{"IOC"} (Immediate Or Cancel): Fill immediately or cancel remainder.
\item \code{"FOK"} (Fill Or Kill): Fill entirely or cancel completely.
}
}

